VThis was my first experience with science fiction,
p19
aVand I loved it.
p20
aVSo when I started to write my own science fiction and fantasy,
p21
aVI was surprised that it was considered un-African.
p22
aVSo naturally, I asked, what is African?
p23
aVAnd this is what I know so far:
p24
aVAfrica is important.
p25
aVAfrica is the future.
p26
aVIt is, though.
p27
aVAnd Africa is a serious place where only serious things happen.
p28
aa(lp29
VSo when I present my work somewhere, someone will always ask,
p30
aV"What's so important about it?
p31
aVHow does it deal with real African issues
p32
aVlike war, poverty, devastation or AIDS?"
p33
aVAnd it doesn't.
p34
aVMy work is about Nairobi pop bands that want to go to space
p35
aVor about seven-foot-tall robots
p36
aVthat fall in love.
p37
aVIt's nothing incredibly important.
p38
aVIt's just fun, fierce and frivolous,
p39
aVas frivolous as bubble gum \u2014
p40
aV"AfroBubbleGum."
p41
aa(lp42
VSo I'm not saying that agenda art isn't important;
p43
aVI'm the chairperson of a charity
p44
aVthat deals with films and theaters that write about HIV and radicalization
p45
aVand female genital mutilation.
p46
aVIt's vital and important art,
p47
aVbut it cannot be the only art that comes out of the continent.
p48
aVWe have to tell more stories
p49
aVthat are vibrant.
p50
aVThe danger of the single story is still being realized.
p51
aVAnd maybe it's because of the funding.
p52
aVA lot of art is still dependent on developmental aid.
p53
aVSo art becomes a tool for agenda.
p54
aVOr maybe it's because we've only seen one image of ourselves for so long
p55
aVthat that's all we know how to create.
p56
aVWhatever the reason, we need a new way,
p57
aVand AfroBubbleGum is one approach.
p58
aVIt's the advocacy of art for art's sake.
p59
aVIt's the advocacy of art that is not policy-driven
p60
aVor agenda-driven
p61
aVor based on education,
p62
aVjust for the sake of imagination:
p63
aVAfroBubbleGum art.
